---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';

const post = {
  title: 'Building High-Performance REST APIs',
  date: '2026-01-10',
  tags: ['APIs', 'Backend', 'Performance'],
};

const formatDate = (dateString: string) => {
  const date = new Date(dateString);
  return date.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });
};
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} - Eben Bentley`}
  name="Eben Bentley"
  description="Design patterns and best practices for building scalable REST APIs. Covers performance optimization, caching strategies, and API versioning."
>
  <Navbar name="Eben Bentley" currentPath="/blog" />

  <div class="container max-w-3xl mx-auto px-8 py-16 sm:px-4">
    <a href="/blog" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-accent hover:underline mb-8">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M15 19l-7-7 7-7" />
      </svg>
      Back to Blog
    </a>

    <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
        <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">{post.title}</h1>

        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-text-secondary">
          <time datetime={post.date}>{formatDate(post.date)}</time>
          <span class="text-border">•</span>
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            {post.tags.map((tag) => (
              <span class="px-2 py-1 rounded-full bg-accent/10 text-accent text-sm font-medium">
                {tag}
              </span>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="border-t border-border pt-8 space-y-6 text-text-primary">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Building high-performance REST APIs requires careful consideration of architecture, design
          patterns, and optimization techniques. This guide covers essential strategies for creating
          scalable, maintainable APIs that can handle production workloads.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">API Design Principles</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          A well-designed API follows RESTful conventions and provides a clean, intuitive interface
          for clients. Key principles include:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Use proper HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH)</li>
          <li>Implement consistent URL patterns and resource naming</li>
          <li>Return appropriate HTTP status codes</li>
          <li>Provide clear error messages with structured error responses</li>
          <li>Version your API to support backward compatibility</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Performance Optimization</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Performance is critical for production APIs. Here are key optimization strategies:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-6 mb-3">1. Caching Strategies</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Implement multi-level caching to reduce database load and improve response times:
        </p>

        <pre class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm">// Application-level caching
cache := NewCache(5 * time.Minute)

func GetUser(id string) (*User, error) {
    if user := cache.Get(id); user != nil {
        return user, nil
    }

    user, err := db.FindUser(id)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }

    cache.Set(id, user)
    return user, nil
}</code></pre>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-6 mb-3">2. Database Query Optimization</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Use database indexes on frequently queried fields</li>
          <li>Implement pagination for large result sets</li>
          <li>Use connection pooling to manage database connections efficiently</li>
          <li>Avoid N+1 query problems by using joins or batch loading</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-6 mb-3">3. Request Rate Limiting</h3>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Protect your API from abuse and ensure fair resource allocation:
        </p>

        <pre class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm">func RateLimitMiddleware(limit int, window time.Duration) Middleware {
    limiter := NewRateLimiter(limit, window)

    return func(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
        return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
            if !limiter.Allow(r.RemoteAddr) {
                http.Error(w, "Rate limit exceeded", 429)
                return
            }
            next.ServeHTTP(w, r)
        })
    }
}</code></pre>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">API Versioning</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Versioning allows you to evolve your API while maintaining backward compatibility. Common approaches include:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>URL versioning: /api/v1/users, /api/v2/users</li>
          <li>Header versioning: Accept: application/vnd.api.v1+json</li>
          <li>Query parameter versioning: /api/users?version=1</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Security Best Practices</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Always use HTTPS in production</li>
          <li>Implement proper authentication and authorization</li>
          <li>Validate and sanitize all input data</li>
          <li>Use JWT tokens or OAuth for stateless authentication</li>
          <li>Implement CORS policies for browser-based clients</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Monitoring and Observability</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Track API performance and health with proper monitoring:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Log request/response cycles with structured logging</li>
          <li>Track response times and latency percentiles</li>
          <li>Monitor error rates and status code distributions</li>
          <li>Set up alerts for anomalies and degraded performance</li>
          <li>Use distributed tracing for microservices architectures</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Building high-performance REST APIs is an iterative process that requires attention to design,
          performance, security, and maintainability. By following these best practices and continuously
          monitoring your API's performance, you can build robust services that scale with your needs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  article.prose {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  article.prose h2,
  article.prose h3 {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  article.prose a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  article.prose a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  article.prose code {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  }

  article.prose ul li {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
</style>
